==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fledge
<hw>Fledge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>flegge</ets>,
<ets>flygge</ets>; akin to D. <ets>vlug</ets>, G. <ets>fl⟦uum⟧gge</ets>,
<ets>fl⟦uum⟧cke</ets>, OHG. <ets>flucchi</ets>, Icel. <ets>fleygr</ets>,
and to E. <ets>fly</ets>. ⟦root⟧84. See <er>Fly</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>Feathered; furnished with feathers or wings; able
to fly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His shoulders, <qex>fledge</qex> with wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fledge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fledge
<hw>Fledge</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fledged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fledging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish with
feathers; to supply with the feathers necessary for flight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The birds were not as yet <qex>fledged</qex> enough to shift for
themselves.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish or adorn with any soft
covering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your master, whose chin is not yet <qex>fledged</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fledged</ent>⟦br⟧
